{"title":"Is It Good Data for Multilingual Instruction Tuning or Just Bad Multilingual Evaluation for Large Language Models?","domain":"LLM_NLP","seeds":[{"problem":"Multilingual instruction tuning often relies on machine-translated data, but it is unclear whether translated instructions are sufficient to match native-language data and whether translated benchmarks faithfully surface any differences.","method":"Run controlled monolingual instruction tuning in Spanish, Russian, and Chinese using either language-native Aya data or size-matched English Aya translated with Google Translate and Cohere Command R (instructions and responses translated separately). Evaluate eight base LLMs (Llama 2, Gemma 2B/7B, Qwen1.5 0.5B–14B) on native vs translated and structured vs generative benchmarks (TyDi QA, C-Eval, CMMLU, XQuAD, MGSM, MT-/HT-MMLU, and open-ended QA scored by GPT-4-Turbo and Command R+), plus a correlation analysis between native performance and the native–translated gap. Results show native-tuned models outperform on language-native and generative tasks (TyDi QA, C-Eval/CMMLU, XQuAD, open-ended QA), while gaps largely vanish on translated structured tests (MGSM, MT-/HT-MMLU); the gap is stronger as base performance rises and for generative evaluations."},{"problem":"If a performance gap exists when using translated instruction data, what causes it more: translation defects (translationese/errors) or missing language-specific knowledge?","method":"Construct round-trip translated (RTT) instruction sets by translating native Russian/Chinese Aya items to English and back (X→en→X), preserving native knowledge while introducing translationese. Train and compare models on RTT data versus single-pass English-origin translations on native tests (TyDi QA ru, CMMLU zh). RTT matches or outperforms English-origin translations—consistently on CMMLU and often on TyDi QA—indicating that missing native, language-specific knowledge in instructions is more detrimental than translation defects."},{"problem":"When native instruction data are unavailable, how can we mitigate the native–translated performance gap in multilingual instruction tuning?","method":"Apply regularization during SFT: (a) reduce learning rate from 1e-4 to 1e-6; (b) perform multilingual instruction tuning by mixing eight languages with balanced sampling. Across larger models, these settings can close or narrow the gap on native structured benchmarks (e.g., lower LR benefits TyDi QA; multilingual tuning helps CMMLU), but they fail to remove the gap on generative tasks (XQuAD, open-ended QA), where native-trained models retain a clear advantage."}]}
